@Hixie I think there is still disconnect from what people are saying. Leave complex animations, garbage collection, expensive builds aside. Even when you create a new project, there is jank in default transitions like navigator push, bottomsheet. If others have experienced the same, they can confirm. Try out your own [navigation tutorial](https://flutter.dev/docs/cookbook/navigation/navigation-basics).

In GPay and some other apps, the scrollview also seems janky first time. Not sure if that is because of expensive build or the issue in discussion. As people have mentioned, some apps seem to be running animations smoothly. NuBank, Reflectly, Insight Timer (scrollview janks in this one). Maybe you guys can talk to them and put out a guide on how to deal with first run jank issues temporarily until there is a longterm framework solution. (Maybe that will stop haters from dunking on Flutter and ruining its reputation. There is already lots of negativity because of this issue.)

@trixky You have already seen @danReynolds solution to warmup animations package which needs multiple runs. We have decided to use minimal animations in our project so not running any complex animations, just dont want the default transitions to jank. To counter navigator push jank, I have a warmup navigator on first run behind the main navigator (code below).

Just experienced today that it works if the push on main navigator comes from gestureDetector onTap but not from floatingActionButton onPressed. So very quirky and unreliable. See if it works for you. This smooths out the navigator push and pop on tap but the swipe back gesture still lags a bit first time. We were also able to smooth out basic slide and rotation transitions by putting them in stack behind the visible layer and calling `.forward` from a timer 300ms after init. This does not need a fake splash screen, the user will anyway take a few seconds to tap something.

`Stack(
          children: [
            _firstRun == true
                ? Builder(
                    builder: (context) {
                      _firstRun = false;
                      WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
                        NWarmup.of(context).addPage();
                        Timer(Duration(milliseconds: 500), () {
                          NWarmup.of(context).removePage();
                        });
                      });
                      return Consumer<NWarmup>(
                        builder: (context, value, child) {
                          return Navigator(
                            key: value.navigatorKey,
                            pages: value.pageStack,
                            onPopPage: (route, result) {
                              return route.didPop(result);
                            },
                          );
                        },
                      );
                    },
                  )
                : SizedBox(),
            // Main navigator
          ],
        )`

@esDotDev Right, generally I would assume this wouldn't help you. Some people have specific needs for which they know this is the solution, and for them this bug would be relevant, but for most people this won't solve their issues and the other things being looked at in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/projects/188 are a better guide (especially any bugs they file specifically about jank they are seeing).

> Anytime I've tried to use the "flame chart" I can't really make heads or tails of it

Sorry to hear that. Might be good to have a boring show episode about how to use it, or some such. Can you file a bug? The more details you can include about the questions you have, the more helpful we can make the documentation!

@acoutts unfortunately Metal performance is quite sluggish when the animations run for the first time (or when app comes from background for example) whereas with OpenGL it runs a lot smoother, even without caching shaders — however, I’ve experienced some random crashes with it, just as you pointed out and reverted to Metal.

I don’t bother caching the shaders if this is needed to improve performance, but seems that this is a no-op with Metal.

I know that this could be quite challenging to fix, but I’d say that it should definitely be prioritised over other issues.

> For example, use the CPU backend when GPU backend needs warm-up.

Rather than using the CPU is it not possible to use more generic GPU shaders? As I understand it the problem is that Skia uses compile time specialisation similar to C++ templates to generate really fast shaders. [Basically `#ifdef`](https://github.com/google/skia/blob/f326e4faef66d529904a7b53eb931fd576c82887/src/gpu/effects/GrEllipseEffect.fp#L105):

```
    @if (medPrecision) {
        approx_dist *= scale.x;
    }

    half alpha;
    @switch (edgeType) {
        case GrClipEdgeType::kFillBW:
            alpha = approx_dist > 0.0 ? 0.0 : 1.0;
            break;
        case GrClipEdgeType::kFillAA:
            alpha = saturate(0.5 - half(approx_dist));
            break;
...
```

Why not just do a dynamic version instead (i.e. use runtime `if`/`switch`)? It'll won't be as fast when warmed up, but presumably not as slow the CPU and the minimum frame rate will be better since it doesn't need to be compiled at runtime.

I'm sure you've thought of this - I just haven't seen it mentioned anywhere so I was curious.
